WEBVTT

00:01.538 --> 00:09.268
As we move from gathering to listening, our scripture reading today is from the book of 2 Timothy, chapter 3, verses 14 through 17.

00:11.111 --> 00:25.170
But as for you, continue in what you have learned and have become convinced of because you know those from whom you learned it and how from infancy you have known the scriptures which are able to make you wise for salvation through faith in Christ Jesus.

00:25.442 --> 00:36.661
All scripture is God breathed and is useful for teaching, rebuking, correcting, and training in righteousness so that the servant of God may be thoroughly equipped for every good work.

00:37.603 --> 00:38.665
This is the word of the Lord.

00:43.173 --> 00:43.994
Thank you, Natalie.

00:44.675 --> 00:45.857
Well, good morning, Antioch.

00:47.179 --> 00:48.542
Good to be with you this morning.

00:48.862 --> 00:51.026
My name's Rick, and I'm one of the elders here.

00:51.842 --> 01:01.712
Today is the third Sunday of harvest, and we're in the third week of a vision series entitled The Whole Gospel, Both and Faith in an Either or World.

01:02.693 --> 01:07.097
I can't tell you how excited I am and how significant I think this series is.

01:07.137 --> 01:14.344
I'd encourage you to be sure to catch every one of these sermons, either in person or by recording.

01:15.946 --> 01:20.210
That doesn't mean I want you to go home now and catch up and walk out on me this morning.

01:20.674 --> 01:27.724
But I truly believe that this series can be transformative, both for us as individuals and collectively in our faith and discipleship.

01:28.885 --> 01:34.413
Today's topic is the whole truth of Scripture, human authorship and divine authority.

01:35.134 --> 01:49.714
We'll be affirming the inspiration and authority of the Bible and discussing the way the scriptures were originally produced and how best to understand the idea that the Holy Spirit of God was involved without overwhelming the

01:49.858 --> 01:52.903
human authors and their personalities and experiences.

01:53.864 --> 02:11.271
And we'll look a little bit at how overemphasis of either the divine authority on the evangelical side or the human authorship on the mainline Protestant side can lead us astray when it comes to understanding God and his purposes in the world and in our lives.

02:12.753 --> 02:18.322
In this series on the whole gospel, most of the topics we face involve false dichotomies.

02:19.106 --> 02:34.082
Christians have tended to choose, for example, whether to believe and teach the gospel of Jesus, what Jesus himself taught, or the gospel about Jesus, what the apostles subsequently taught about the purpose and meaning of Jesus' life and death.

02:35.023 --> 02:38.547
And as Pete showed us last week, the two are not mutually exclusive.

02:38.727 --> 02:40.970
They don't even appear to contradict one another.

02:41.010 --> 02:48.338
And there's no reason to choose between the two and every reason to proclaim and live out both.

02:48.898 --> 02:53.565
And the same is true of most of the other issues we will address in this series.

02:53.685 --> 02:55.428
They're simply false dichotomies.

02:56.509 --> 03:02.839
But may I suggest that today's topic, and I believe just one or two of the others, involves a paradox.

03:04.441 --> 03:13.134
And when introducing the concept of paradox, I can do no better than pointing you to Gilbert and Sullivan's fun-loving musical, The Pirates of Penzance.

03:13.154 --> 03:18.802
In the second act, we find the song when you had left our pirate fold whose chorus goes like this.

03:19.842 --> 03:23.827
a paradox, a paradox, a most ingenious paradox.

03:23.847 --> 03:47.474
Ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha ha

03:48.354 --> 03:53.462
And so he spends his youth aboard a pirate ship learning the ways of a very musical band of buccaneers.

03:54.604 --> 03:55.926
The paradox is this.

03:56.687 --> 04:01.855
Frederick's contract for his apprenticeship frees him from the pirates on his 21st birthday.

04:02.917 --> 04:08.045
But he was born on February 29th, which comes around only every four years.

04:08.887 --> 04:13.554
So although he has lived 21 years, he has only experienced five birthdays.

04:15.266 --> 04:18.229
A paradox is an apparent contradiction.

04:18.609 --> 04:25.536
Usually, a pair of statements or beliefs that seem to be logically inconsistent with one another, but which, in fact, are not.

04:26.777 --> 04:30.500
Here's an example from science, the oxygen ultraviolet paradox.

04:31.281 --> 04:45.074
Science textbooks still talk about the Miller-Urey experiment of the 1950s in which Miller briefly produced a smattering of amino acids in an effort to explain how chemical evolution could have led to the building blocks of life.

04:45.730 --> 04:51.619
We now know that the conditions under which the experiment was performed were inaccurate to the early Earth.

04:52.440 --> 05:01.054
Miller carefully kept oxygen away from the experimental apparatus because he knew that the building blocks of life cannot be produced in the presence of free oxygen.

05:02.115 --> 05:14.194
But in the absence of oxygen on the early Earth, there would have been no ozone layer and harmful ultraviolet radiation would have immediately destroyed any building blocks of life as soon as they formed.

05:14.786 --> 05:21.776
The chemical evolution of life's building blocks cannot take place either in the absence or in the presence of oxygen.

05:23.018 --> 05:33.434
In this case, the paradox cannot be resolved except by recognition that the starting assumption that life evolved gradually and without God's intervention is wrong.

05:34.175 --> 05:44.210
The oxygen UV paradox therefore provides further support for the idea that first and simplest life was a miracle and that DNA, proteins, and such

05:44.450 --> 05:49.015
cannot be produced except within a fully viable functioning living cell.

05:50.517 --> 05:51.898
Okay, that's your science for the day.

05:52.880 --> 06:00.789
There'll be a little survey on your way out as to whether you found the science illustration or the Pirates of Pennsylvania's illustration more helpful.

06:01.910 --> 06:02.991
Now back to the main point.

06:04.172 --> 06:07.977
The Bible and Christian faith include a number of paradoxes.

06:08.818 --> 06:12.722
We affirm, for example, that God is three and that God is one.

06:13.282 --> 06:19.272
And it takes a further bit of digging and explanation to resolve these two seemingly contradictory ideas.

06:20.093 --> 06:25.242
This particular paradox has been a stumbling block over the centuries for Jews and Muslims, among others.

06:26.264 --> 06:31.613
Likewise, we confess that Jesus is fully human and fully divine at the same time.

06:32.434 --> 06:39.666
I won't go into any detail on that because sometime in the next few weeks, Sean or someone even brighter will make that one

06:40.898 --> 06:43.443
We'll make that one the focus of one of these sermons.

06:45.947 --> 06:52.980
Here's a paradox that has divided Christendom throughout the centuries and not across the conservative liberal spectrum of these other topics.

06:53.641 --> 07:04.882
The camp that came to be known as Calvinism asserts vigorously that God is completely sovereign over all that occurs, including over which human beings are elect and therefore enter Christ's kingdom.

07:05.026 --> 07:14.500
Whereas the Arminian camp just as vigorously asserts the truth of human free will and responsibility, including regarding each person's individual salvation.

07:15.722 --> 07:28.642
And without getting into the weeds of where each of these views might tend to go too far in support of their position, the relevant point this morning is that the Bible teaches both God's sovereignty and human free will and responsibility.

07:29.183 --> 07:31.506
So this constitutes another paradox.

07:32.482 --> 07:38.130
In addition, in some biblical and Christian paradoxes, there remains, at the end of the day, mystery.

07:38.791 --> 07:43.758
And we cannot fully comprehend or explain everything there is to know about the resolution of them.

07:44.499 --> 07:48.465
This is okay because we also affirm a God who is beyond our comprehension.

07:49.106 --> 07:57.819
As God himself declared through the prophet Isaiah, for my thoughts are not your thoughts, neither are your ways, my ways, declares the Lord.

07:58.400 --> 08:00.082
As the heavens are higher than the earth,

08:00.354 --> 08:04.239
So are my ways higher than your ways and my thoughts than your thoughts.

08:05.581 --> 08:16.915
To put it another way, if we have our theology too finely tuned, bundled up and impregnable, then we've likely created God in our own image rather than accepted his own self-revelation.

08:18.157 --> 08:28.210
A wise messianic Jewish lady friend of mine tells me that the idea of having a complete systematic theology, a concept treasured by Western Christians,

08:28.322 --> 08:37.673
is completely foreign to the Jewish mind, which instead allows God to be God, even when that leaves a lot of room for mystery and in comprehension.

08:39.595 --> 08:50.147
Returning to the issue before us today, it seems contradictory to say that what we have in the Bible is the Word of God, and at the same time, the writings of nearly 40 different human authors.

08:52.530 --> 08:56.274
But this is and always has been the Christian belief

08:56.354 --> 08:59.719
And it was certainly the belief of all the writers of Scripture themselves.

09:00.401 --> 09:10.016
And so we here at Antioch affirm with that vast cloud of witnesses both the human agency in the writing of the Bible and the divine authority of Scripture.

09:10.717 --> 09:16.607
We uphold the doctrines of the inspiration and authority of the Bible, believing it to be the very word of God.

09:17.428 --> 09:23.378
And we believe that the individual human authors, their contexts, personalities, and experiences

09:23.490 --> 09:26.454
matter to our proper understanding of their words.

09:27.656 --> 09:33.405
And we do our best to keep these two, the divine authority and the human authorship, in their proper balance.

09:34.466 --> 09:42.017
A minute ago, as I introduced the quote from Isaiah, the words I used were, as God himself declared through the prophet Isaiah.

09:43.099 --> 09:47.185
And this would be a variation of the formula that we should always have in mind.

09:48.066 --> 09:50.770
I know brothers and sisters who almost never say,

09:51.074 --> 10:01.448
Paul wrote to the Colossians or as David said in the 23rd Psalm, instead they would always and invariably say the word of God says.

10:02.029 --> 10:02.790
And that's okay.

10:04.933 --> 10:17.330
But if at Antioch we tend to say in his gospel account Luke wrote or something like that, we're never intending to ignore or downplay the fact that the Holy Spirit was inspiring Luke.

10:17.986 --> 10:28.458
Instead, our both and faith affirms with Jews and Christians throughout the ages that what the human authors of the Bible wrote was exactly what God wanted them to write.

10:29.719 --> 10:36.627
So let's look briefly at where we receive this understanding by examining some of the scriptures and what they have to say about themselves.

10:37.468 --> 10:42.033
And let's start with a passage in which Jesus himself offers us this same formula.

10:43.795 --> 10:46.418
And as Jesus taught in the temple, he said,

10:46.530 --> 10:49.595
How can the scribes say that Christ is the son of David?

10:50.556 --> 10:59.589
David himself, in the Holy Spirit, declared, the Lord said to my Lord, sit at my right hand until I put your enemies under your feet.

11:00.871 --> 11:06.760
The primary point of this passage is Jesus' own understanding of his identity as David's eternal Lord.

11:07.481 --> 11:16.114
But the point for us this morning is how Jesus understood this psalm, which is as the product of David writing in the power of the Holy Spirit.

11:16.866 --> 11:22.833
And this is the consistent understanding of the writers of the New Testament with regard to the Hebrew Scriptures.

11:22.853 --> 11:27.618
2 Peter 2, 20, and 21.

11:28.499 --> 11:35.047
Above all, you must understand that no prophecy of Scripture came about by the prophet's own interpretation of things.

11:35.728 --> 11:44.498
For prophecy never had its origin in the human will, but prophets, though human, spoke from God as they were carried along by the Holy Spirit.

11:45.058 --> 11:50.585
So this represents Peter's articulation of the both and nature of the scripture writing process.

11:51.847 --> 11:54.790
Now let's turn to the passage that Natalie read first this morning.

11:54.810 --> 12:06.685
2 Timothy 3, 16 and 17 says that, all scripture is God breathed and is useful for teaching, rebuking, collecting, I'm sorry, correcting and training and righteousness.

12:07.246 --> 12:08.688
I needed to correct myself there.

12:10.190 --> 12:13.714
So that the servant of God may be thoroughly equipped for every good work.

12:14.434 --> 12:22.304
This passage is probably the clearest statement of the doctrine of the inspiration of Scripture, the involvement of God's Spirit in the writing of the Bible.

12:23.506 --> 12:33.979
It's referring specifically to what we call the Old Testament because at the time Paul wrote these words to Timothy, the Scriptures were limited to the Hebrew Torah, wisdom, literature, and the writings of the prophets.

12:35.140 --> 12:36.402
But as we'll see in a minute,

12:36.546 --> 12:45.339
This understanding of what constitutes the scripture was also being extended to include the writings of the apostles and what we now call the New Testament.

12:46.801 --> 13:01.323
All the evidence available to us confirms that there was a monolithic understanding among the Jews that the Hebrew scriptures were the writings of men that were inspired by God, that they were the very word of God recorded through the agency of human beings.

13:02.144 --> 13:06.290
And the patriarchs, kings, judges, and prophets themselves

13:06.402 --> 13:08.284
reflected that same understanding.

13:09.025 --> 13:18.334
And their writings are filled with phrases like, thus says the Lord, or the Lord instructed me to write these words, or the equivalent.

13:18.354 --> 13:26.602
At any rate, we see in 2 Timothy 3, 16 that the purpose of God's inspiring these writings includes teaching, rebuking, correcting, and training.

13:27.383 --> 13:34.930
And if we back up to the preceding verses, we find that the Scriptures also are able to make us wise for salvation through faith in Christ Jesus.

13:35.938 --> 13:50.179
But as for you, continue in what you have learned and have become convinced of because you know those from whom you learned it and how from infancy you have known the Holy Scriptures, which are able to make you wise for salvation through faith in Christ Jesus.

13:51.641 --> 13:53.564
Here Paul makes mention of two different things.

13:54.305 --> 13:58.912
One, what Timothy was taught about Jesus and his kingdom by his mother and grandmother.

13:58.952 --> 14:00.434
And second,

14:00.546 --> 14:07.314
how the Hebrew Scriptures that he knew well from childhood also pointed ahead to the gospel of salvation in Christ.

14:08.556 --> 14:18.568
But as I suggested, we can also see hints that the apostles involved in the writing of the New Testament also recognized that what they were writing was God's inspired word as well.

14:19.469 --> 14:22.633
Here's an example from 2 Peter, so Peter writing.

14:23.774 --> 14:30.162
Bear in mind that our Lord's patience means salvation, just as our dear brother Paul also wrote to you,

14:30.274 --> 14:32.116
with the wisdom that God gave him.

14:32.977 --> 14:36.822
He writes the same way in all his letters speaking in them of these matters.

14:37.383 --> 14:47.275
His letters contain some things that are hard to understand which ignorant and unstable people distort as they do the other scriptures to their own destruction.

14:48.157 --> 14:58.770
So here Peter demonstrates awareness of Paul's letters, declares that they are written with the wisdom of God and equates them with the other scriptures.

15:00.066 --> 15:03.471
Paul similarly refers to Luke's gospel as scripture.

15:04.853 --> 15:13.866
In 1 Timothy 518, for scripture says, do not muzzle an ox while it is treading out the grain, and the worker deserves his wages.

15:14.407 --> 15:16.130
So he quotes two passages here.

15:16.670 --> 15:21.998
The first, do not muzzle an ox, comes from Deuteronomy 25, 4, the Hebrew scriptures.

15:22.779 --> 15:29.970
But the second, the worker deserves his wages, comes from Luke 10, 7, and is a quotation of Jesus.

15:30.594 --> 15:36.042
According to Paul here, Luke's gospel is scripture on the same level as the Hebrew scriptures.

15:37.324 --> 15:46.857
And John and Luke and the other New Testament writers all share this understanding of what they were doing as writing the very word of God under the inspiration of God's own Holy Spirit.

15:47.638 --> 15:52.365
And this situation was prophesied by Jesus himself as recorded in John 1426.

15:54.388 --> 15:58.674
But the advocate, this is Jesus speaking, but the advocate, the Holy Spirit,

15:58.818 --> 16:05.605
whom the Father will send in my name will teach you all things and will remind you of everything I have said to you.

16:06.485 --> 16:16.995
Here Jesus is recorded as promising the disciples that the Holy Spirit would empower them to remember and record without error all that Jesus had said.

16:17.035 --> 16:27.986
And we could go on and on looking at passages that help lay out this paradoxical doctrine of the simultaneous human authorship and divine authority of the Scriptures.

16:28.834 --> 16:35.783
And so far, all we've talked about is the result, the fact that the words of the Bible written by humans are nonetheless the words of God.

16:36.664 --> 16:39.188
Now I want to briefly mention the process.

16:40.469 --> 16:52.545
Among evangelicals who tend to emphasize the divine aspect of the Bible, the tendency is to envision a process of dictation, whereby God tells the human author exactly what to write, and he writes it.

16:53.647 --> 16:56.050
Where this does occur, it is often obvious.

16:56.194 --> 17:06.506
In Isaiah 38, for example, we read, then the word of the Lord came to Isaiah, go and tell Hezekiah, this is what the Lord, the God of your father David says.

17:06.546 --> 17:17.538
In the book of Revelation, John saw the risen Lord in a vision, and Jesus spoke to him saying, to the angel of the church at Ephesus, write, and that's what John wrote.

17:18.580 --> 17:20.722
These are clear examples of dictation.

17:21.474 --> 17:26.340
But in the majority of cases, this is not what was going on when the Scriptures were written.

17:27.522 --> 17:31.187
Probably on the other end of the spectrum is Luke's case.

17:31.207 --> 17:46.927
Writing about his process, Luke begins his gospel by saying, many have undertaken to draw up an account of the things that have been fulfilled among us, just as they were handed down to us by those who from the first were eyewitnesses and servants of the word.

17:47.868 --> 17:49.170
With this in mind,

17:49.250 --> 17:58.522
Since I myself have carefully investigated everything from the beginning, I too decided to write an orderly account for you most excellent Theophilus.

17:59.744 --> 18:04.289
This would seem to be far from the process of dictation that we saw at work a minute ago.

18:04.350 --> 18:17.106
Apparently, Luke used the ordinary methods of journalism, questioning eyewitnesses and gathering all of the relevant information that would allow him to write an accurate account of Jesus' life and teachings.

18:18.370 --> 18:21.895
And so here is where we probably have to be content with a bit of mystery.

18:22.557 --> 18:26.362
Scripture doesn't tell us how the process took place in most cases.

18:27.003 --> 18:34.315
And we can only affirm with the writer of Hebrews that, quote, God spoke to our fathers in many and various ways.

18:35.417 --> 18:37.941
We'll come back to the mystery at the end of this sermon.

18:39.243 --> 18:44.050
Okay, so far we've been trying to lay out the case for the both and nature of this topic.

18:44.194 --> 18:48.962
Now I want to look at the problems associated with either or thinking on this subject.

18:50.104 --> 18:58.640
And I should start by saying that most of the church, there's a large part in the middle of the church, which would affirm both the human authorship and the divine authority.

18:59.020 --> 19:01.264
So I'm really talking about the extremes.

19:02.086 --> 19:09.138
I'm going to focus on the extremes describing how emphasizing either half to the ignoring of the other can lead to error.

19:09.762 --> 19:18.056
Again, this will involve generalizations and are not meant as an indictment of any individual or group, but you may nonetheless recognize what I'm talking about.

19:19.338 --> 19:25.769
On the evangelical side, the great strength is the insistence that the Scriptures are indeed the very word of God.

19:26.850 --> 19:33.842
But the first problem I want to call out is what I'll call verse picking, and I'll let Christian apologists Greg Cokal describe it.

19:34.946 --> 19:47.767
Evangelicals have developed a dangerous habit of looking for verses or isolated phrases in the Bibles that they think the Spirit impresses on them with personal messages foreign to the original context.

19:48.528 --> 19:51.573
Experiences like these are powerful but problematic.

19:52.154 --> 19:59.666
He goes on to say, the Bible itself teaches that God chose specific words meant to communicate precise meanings.

20:00.258 --> 20:07.049
Looking for private messages in passages originally intended to mean something else, interferes with that divine intent.

20:07.950 --> 20:12.517
Instead, the Bible tells us to study to get the correct sense of a passage.

20:13.298 --> 20:17.204
Then we are to guard and protect that truth from distortion and abuse.

20:18.827 --> 20:23.314
Koko's own remedy for this problem is simply never read a Bible verse.

20:23.970 --> 20:33.862
By this he means that in order to make sure you have the context and therefore the meaning of a verse right, you need to read at least the entire paragraph if not the whole chapter or more.

20:35.083 --> 20:36.285
Let me give you one example.

20:37.286 --> 20:50.962
The entire left behind series of books and movies that sprung out of evangelicalism in the late 20th century came about by lifting a verse out of its context in order to make it say the opposite of what it really says.

20:51.842 --> 21:04.036
This recent misinterpretation takes its title from the words of Jesus in four verses in two passages, Matthew 24, 40, and 41, and Luke 17, 34, and 35.

21:04.316 --> 21:14.388
It promotes the rapture and idea that arose in the 19th century that says that when Jesus returns at the end of this age, it is to take his followers away to heaven.

21:15.209 --> 21:19.474
According to this view, we don't want to be the ones left behind on earth.

21:20.450 --> 21:39.709
but reading the entire paragraph in either passage where he used these words left behind, Jesus makes it clear that he is saying that those taken away are taken to judgment and those left behind will be saved to participate in his forever kingdom here on the renewed earth.

21:41.791 --> 21:45.775
Associated with this problem is another dangerous one and that's biblicism.

21:46.556 --> 21:48.338
It's reflected in the bumper sticker

21:48.514 --> 21:50.896
God said it, I believe it, that settles it.

21:52.458 --> 21:58.244
Biblicism is the claim that the only things that we can know for sure are what the Bible tells us.

21:58.264 --> 22:00.186
And there are at least three problems with it.

22:00.987 --> 22:03.750
First, biblicism is self-refuting.

22:04.991 --> 22:07.934
That is, the claim itself falsifies itself.

22:08.835 --> 22:11.938
So here's a silly example of a self-refuting statement.

22:12.679 --> 22:15.602
There are no sentences in English of more than three words.

22:16.674 --> 22:19.137
This statement fails its own test.

22:19.758 --> 22:21.800
It is self-referentially absurd.

22:21.840 --> 22:26.666
Here's a more serious one that we commonly hear in our scientific age.

22:27.707 --> 22:31.211
The only way of truly knowing something is through scientific testing.

22:32.493 --> 22:41.143
This is an attempt to artificially narrow what counts as knowledge, thereby eliminating such things as revelation or faith.

22:41.844 --> 22:43.826
But it too is self-refuting.

22:44.130 --> 22:53.919
Because there is no scientific experiment that can yield the conclusion that the only way of truly knowing something is through scientific testing, okay?

22:53.939 --> 22:56.001
Biblicism suffers the same fate.

22:56.742 --> 23:04.209
If the claim of biblicism were true, it would have to come from Scripture, but there is no passage of Scripture that makes such a claim.

23:05.250 --> 23:14.098
Secondly, and instead, we find in Scripture many appeals or even mandates telling us to search for and find truth in history,

23:14.242 --> 23:18.628
Nature, reason, our own conscience, and through other avenues.

23:19.349 --> 23:33.929
The clearest appeals to nature as a guide to knowing God are found in Psalm 19 and Romans 1, the latter of which tells us that all people know from the evidence of the creation itself that there is a God, though many choose to reject that knowledge.

23:35.431 --> 23:43.442
Thirdly, one cannot begin to understand scripture without bringing to it an entire range of knowledge gained from outside of scripture.

23:43.874 --> 23:48.800
This includes such things as vocabulary and grammar, the laws of logic and such.

23:50.082 --> 23:55.789
Like scientism, biblicism is an attempt to artificially discount other roots to knowledge.

23:56.590 --> 24:02.277
In modern evangelicalism, biblicism is a favorite ploy of young earth creation organizations.

24:02.938 --> 24:12.370
And anytime you hear an appeal to biblicism or to scientism, you can feel pretty certain that the interpretation being defended cannot stand up to scrutiny.

24:14.146 --> 24:22.816
Closely associated with biblicism is the tendency to act as though the Bible were written in English and directly for 21st century Christians.

24:23.838 --> 24:32.548
This can lead to sloppy interpretation that ignores the original language, culture, history, and experiences essential to the proper reading.

24:32.588 --> 24:40.658
Accurate understanding what the Bible has to say to us depends upon rightly recognizing the various genres in which it is written.

24:41.250 --> 24:46.277
We get into trouble very quickly, for example, if we treat a proverb as a promise.

24:47.439 --> 24:48.461
Here's Proverb 22.6.

24:48.841 --> 24:54.790
Start children off on the way they should go, and even when they're old, they will turn from it.

24:55.952 --> 25:06.548
Many evangelical parents have claimed this as a promise from God, only to find that one of their teenager adult children does, in fact, turn from the faith and morality of their parents.

25:07.269 --> 25:08.250
Has God failed them?

25:08.631 --> 25:10.834
Has he failed to carry out his promise here?

25:11.682 --> 25:20.434
Well, no, and that's because this is not a promise, but a proverb, not an unfailing law, but a bit of wisdom that we would do well to follow.

25:22.517 --> 25:28.285
But in addition to genre, historical context matters and a knowledge of Greek and Hebrew are helpful.

25:29.206 --> 25:40.722
This is not to say that you need to be a scholar in Greek and Hebrew to understand a given passage, but it is certainly important to seek out from time to time a brother or sister who is familiar with these ancient languages

25:40.866 --> 25:43.269
when wrestling with a difficult portion of scripture.

25:44.751 --> 25:49.677
Let me give you just a quick, a couple of quick examples and these come from the key passage for this morning.

25:50.218 --> 25:50.939
Here it is again.

25:50.959 --> 25:58.729
All scripture is God breathed and is useful for teaching, rebuking, correcting, and training in righteousness.

26:00.171 --> 26:05.498
In English, there are two different words that are used to translate the single Greek word dikaiosune.

26:06.279 --> 26:08.882
One is righteousness is found here in this verse.

26:09.442 --> 26:19.019
And when we think of righteousness, we usually have in mind personal individual moral purity, but the scriptures rarely have that meaning in mind.

26:19.800 --> 26:27.434
The other word used to translate this word is justice, which we understand mean right relationship with others.

26:28.195 --> 26:34.546
The scriptures usually have something more like this in mind, and justice is probably the better translation for this passage.

26:36.258 --> 26:43.092
But in actuality, we should understand this Greek word dikaiosune to mean something much more like the Hebrew word shalom.

26:44.194 --> 26:58.322
Paul is not here telling us that the Scriptures can train us merely toward personal moral purity, but to reconciliation in all spheres and to right relationship with God, self, others, and the rest of creation.

26:58.914 --> 27:07.567
Here, failure to dig into the original language will leave us with rather too tepid an understanding of what God really has in store for us.

27:07.587 --> 27:14.037
Moving on in that same verse, so that the servant of God may be thoroughly equipped for every good work.

27:15.459 --> 27:17.462
Let's look at the word here translated servant.

27:17.663 --> 27:21.228
It is the Greek word anthropos, and it doesn't mean servant.

27:22.430 --> 27:27.698
As with all Greek nouns, anthropos is gendered, and it happens to be a masculine noun.

27:28.226 --> 27:31.511
but this does not mean that it only refers to male persons.

27:32.513 --> 27:50.782
But because it is a masculine noun and because it makes for a smoother reading, the NIV, until very recently, and many other English translations still today, have translated it in this passage and elsewhere as simply man, so that the man of God may be thoroughly equipped for every good work.

27:51.583 --> 27:56.050
That translation wrongly implies that female disciples are not in view here.

27:56.738 --> 28:06.438
A truer translation would be so that the human being of God or so that the individual of God would be equipped for every good work.

28:07.139 --> 28:18.482
But the translation here, the servant of God, is a great improvement upon the old rendering of man, even though it loses a little bit in terms of exact word-for-word translation of the Greek.

28:20.130 --> 28:26.637
Let me turn now to the mainline Protestant side, where the danger is overemphasis of the human authorship of the Scriptures.

28:27.498 --> 28:37.790
Again, speaking in generalities, the mainline Protestant believer is much more likely to pay attention to all of the considerations I've been talking about that are associated with the human authorship of the Bible.

28:38.250 --> 28:41.774
Things like genre, historical context, the original language, and such.

28:42.295 --> 28:43.216
And all this is good.

28:44.137 --> 28:48.562
But let me identify two problems, or rather two levels of the same problem,

28:48.674 --> 28:55.284
that can result from an over-emphasis on the human authorship and an under-emphasis of the divine authority of Scripture.

28:55.985 --> 29:00.512
And while this won't take as long, the problem can be even more dire in its consequences.

29:01.754 --> 29:14.674
On one level, careful study of the Bible that pays close attention to genre, language, historical context, and such can lead to a place where the student of the Bible is involved in nothing more than an academic exercise.

29:15.138 --> 29:25.971
He may come to forget or disregard the important fact that what he is studying is the very word of God, the self-revelation of the Almighty God of the universe through humans to humans.

29:26.812 --> 29:29.255
It's a case of not seeing the forest for the trees.

29:30.076 --> 29:44.914
In focusing on the details on the minutiae, important as they may be to grasping a proper understanding, it can be easy to miss the opportunity to commune with the divine author, even while pouring intensely over the love letter he has written to us.

29:46.306 --> 29:49.611
But there is another and even more dangerous level of this same problem.

29:50.312 --> 29:56.802
Becoming too absorbed in the details of the human authorship can lead to complete rejection of the divine authority of Scripture.

29:57.903 --> 30:10.482
As strange as it may sound to some of us, a 2020 Barna survey found that 25% of Christians no longer believe that the Bible is the Word of God or that it is reliable and trustworthy.

30:11.426 --> 30:23.798
It's tempting to call this a slippery slope, but I suspect that it's more accurate to see it as a steep precipice or cliff, because God chose to reveal himself to us through human language and human authors with all their frailties.

30:24.499 --> 30:39.794
And because the copying, preserving, and translation of Scripture also has involved humans at every step of the way, there can be a temptation to focus too closely on this aspect of this mysterious process and arrive at the conclusion that God was not involved at all.

30:40.514 --> 30:50.308
From doubting God's involvement in the writing of the Bible, to doubting God's involvement in creation itself, to doubting God's very existence is a rather easy series of steps.

30:51.510 --> 31:02.146
So here at Antioch, we are committed to affirming, both in our proclamation and by our practice, both the human authorship and the divine authority of the Scriptures, the Word of God.

31:02.967 --> 31:07.954
And although everything we've discussed this morning has focused on the giving and receiving of this great gift,

31:08.354 --> 31:13.179
We likewise affirm both the human and divine aspect to the unwrapping of it.

31:14.580 --> 31:22.948
This is another sermon altogether, but we also approach Bible reading as a collaborative enterprise between our human selves and the Holy Spirit of God.

31:23.768 --> 31:38.322
And so each time we open the scriptures, we should be asking the Holy Spirit to illuminate them for us, to teach us a deeper understanding, even of words that we've read innumerable times, and to change our hearts and minds wherever such change is still needed.

31:38.434 --> 31:40.017
as we engage with his word.

31:41.680 --> 31:46.888
I've suggested that we must be content with accepting that there is mystery in the process of getting God's word to us.

31:47.489 --> 31:50.274
And yet, perhaps it's not such a great mystery after all.

31:51.236 --> 31:55.964
Isn't life with both its material and immaterial aspects a greater mystery?

31:57.066 --> 32:04.178
The historical Christian understanding, and this about something for which the naturalist scientist has absolutely no explanation,

32:04.866 --> 32:19.441
is that at conception, not only does a new physical life begin to form, but that new living creature is simultaneously imbued with soul, spirit, conscience, and all of the other mental and immaterial components that make up human life.

32:20.622 --> 32:32.434
One of my favorite lines from Christian songwriter Rich Mullins is this, we are frail, we are fearfully and wonderfully made, forged in the fires of human passion, choking on the fumes of selfish rage.

32:33.346 --> 32:40.918
The first line proclaims God's involvement, while the rest acknowledges the specifically human act that goes to creating a new human life.

32:41.920 --> 32:47.208
It may only take two detango, but it takes God's contribution to bring about the miracle of life.

32:48.871 --> 32:54.019
Then again, the creator of the universe is condescended to give humans charge over the rest of creation.

32:54.600 --> 32:55.922
How mysterious is that?

32:57.282 --> 33:06.941
In Psalm 8, the shepherd astronomer David, inspired by the Holy Spirit, reminds us of this willingness on God's part to use us humans to accomplish His will for creation.

33:07.602 --> 33:11.269
You have made them a little lower than the angels and crowned them with glory and honor.

33:11.810 --> 33:14.035
You made them rulers over the works of your hands.

33:14.516 --> 33:16.179
You put everything under their feet.

33:17.822 --> 33:19.826
And then, what about the incarnation?

33:20.546 --> 33:32.601
The paradoxical nature of the writing of scripture seems a little less mysterious when compared to the fact that the God of the universe became a human being in order, in part, to communicate to us what God is like.

33:34.083 --> 33:43.655
And consider this, whenever God chooses to communicate to humans, it necessarily involves his condescending to use human language and human speech.

33:44.356 --> 33:49.522
And often he uses the voices of other humans, whether prophets or wise mentors.

33:50.466 --> 33:57.934
Maybe your homework assignment should be to spend a half hour thinking about how and in what language the Father speaks to the Son through all eternity.

33:58.915 --> 34:02.219
What language the Holy Spirit uses when instructing the angels?

34:02.939 --> 34:08.325
Or how Christ communicates to the birds, the waters of the ocean, or the whales that sport within them?

34:09.787 --> 34:16.434
The point is that while there remains mystery in the simultaneous divine and human authorship of the Bible,

34:16.802 --> 34:24.681
There are other mysteries even greater that we must accept when in the presence of an uncreated everlasting Almighty God.

